A Mathematical Model of Humility and Ethical Intelligence}
\author{U Ingar Soe \\ Founder of THEISM (Transformative Humility and Ethical Intelligence System Model) \\ Creator of the Paṭiccasamuppāda Engine, Architect of Poormanmeism}
\date{October 2025}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
This paper introduces the \textit{Poormanmeism Algorithmic Framework} (PAF), a novel mathematical and philosophical model designed to capture humility as the initiating principle of ethical intelligence. The framework proposes an iterative process, beginning with a ``Humble Reset,'' which evolves through stages of knowledge acquisition, ethical evaluation, and recursive feedback. We formalize these steps using algorithmic and mathematical structures, aiming to provide a foundation for both theoretical philosophy and potential applications in ethical artificial intelligence (AI) systems. This work is inspired by Buddhist causality (Paṭiccasamuppāda), yet reformulated in rigorous mathematical language.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Modern mathematics and artificial intelligence often emphasize optimization, efficiency, and utility. However, ethical intelligence requires a different foundation: humility. This paper develops a new mathematical formulation---the \textbf{Poormanmeism Algorithmic Framework (PAF)}---which treats humility as the initial condition for knowledge and ethical action.

PAF can be viewed as both:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A philosophical contribution: redefining the basis of ethical reasoning in algorithmic terms.
    \item A mathematical system: formalizing recursive causal dependencies using symbolic and algorithmic structures.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Mathematical Formulation}

We define the iterative system of PAF as follows.

\subsection{Initialization: Humble Reset}
The initial condition represents epistemic humility:
\begin{equation}
H_0 = \{\, K = 0,\, O = 0 \,\}
\end{equation}
where $K$ denotes knowledge and $O$ denotes ownership (resources or ego-claims).

\subsection{Recursive Ethical Intelligence Function}
We define the recursive mapping:
\begin{equation}
S_{t+1} = f(S_t, E_t)
\end{equation}
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $S_t$ is the state of intelligence at iteration $t$,
    \item $E_t$ is the ethical evaluation function applied at time $t$,
    \item $f$ encodes both causality and feedback.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Causality Chain}
We formalize the progression through causal links:
\begin{equation}
C = \{\, H \rightarrow K \rightarrow R \rightarrow E \rightarrow A \,\}
\end{equation}
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $H$ = Humility,
    \item $K$ = Knowledge acquisition,
    \item $R$ = Reasoning process,
    \item $E$ = Ethical evaluation,
    \item $A$ = Action.
\end{itemize}

Thus, PAF is a structured causal map:
\begin{equation}
A = \Phi(H,K,R,E)
\end{equation}
with $\Phi$ representing the Poormanmeism transformation.

\subsection{Feedback Loop}
Ethical action influences the next cycle:
\begin{equation}
H_{t+1} = g(H_t, A_t)
\end{equation}
where humility is recalibrated after every action, sustaining the recursive learning.

\section{Discussion}
The PAF model is designed to unify ethics, humility, and algorithmic intelligence in one system. Unlike conventional optimization frameworks, which prioritize efficiency or utility, PAF begins with an explicit \textbf{zero-state humility} and evolves recursively. The model draws inspiration from Paṭiccasamuppāda (dependent origination in Buddhist philosophy), but adapts it into a formal, symbolic-mathematical structure.  

Potential applications include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Ethical AI design where systems must learn from humility-based resets.
    \item Decision-making frameworks under uncertainty.
    \item Philosophical modeling of ethical causality.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
This paper presents the first formulation of the Poormanmeism Algorithmic Framework (PAF). Future research may involve computational simulations, proofs of stability under recursive operations, and integration with machine learning architectures.

